@C axis-k-known-bounds :: meta [4!]
  <- axis-k-raw-91-C3-honest-disclosures
  B1 = "introduced_at is OPTIONAL. Required only on rows added after the axis-K cutover (2026-04-28). Foundation rows ([11*]) MAY carry sentinel 'foundation' or omit. Legacy rows MAY carry sentinel 'pre-axis-K'."
  B2 = "origin_shard accepts ONE slug. Multi-origin rows (cross-pollination synth-edges from N>1 shards) demote secondary origins to comment prose. SAME pattern as axis-J's superseded_by bound."
  B3 = "axis-K is non-actuating like axis-I and axis-J. This shard is a DESIGN PROPOSAL; converting existing rows to use introduced_at + origin_shard is a SEPARATE migration step requiring chflags unlock + bulk lint pass + re-flag. NOT in this shard."
  B4 = "axis-G K_core grows 15 → 18 (introduced_at + origin_shard + superseded_at). Within the 20-30 ceiling estimate. Future axes L, M may have 2-12 fields of headroom remaining."
  B5 = "Date type accepts ISO 8601 'YYYY-MM-DD' and RFC 3339 'YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SSZ'. Timezone offsets (e.g. '+09:00') are accepted; non-UTC timestamps are normalised to UTC at validation time. Sub-day precision is OPTIONAL — most rows will use date-only form."
  B6 = "Scope contract: this shard does NOT modify any existing row. It does NOT add introduced_at to foundation rows. Migration would happen in a future commit, with chflags unlock + bulk lint + re-flag — NOT in this shard."
  B7 = "axis-K is a BACKWARD-LOOKING (birth-side) axis. axis-J handled FORWARD-LOOKING (death-side). Together they form the complete row-lifecycle quartet {introduced_at, origin_shard, superseded_at, superseded_by}. Future axes addressing MUTATION (mid-life edits, refinements) are not in scope here — that would be axis-L territory."
  B8 = "axis-K's [N*GOLDED] suffix introduces a phase keyword that overlaps with the existing folkloric 골화 marker in shard-header comments (line 7, 17349). The choice to use English 'GOLDED' (a coined past-tense of 골화) rather than 'CALCIFIED' or 'STABILISED' is a judgement call — atlas.n6 prose is bilingual (Korean+English) and GOLDED preserves the 골화 root while remaining ASCII-parseable. Defer alternative-phrasing votes to future cycles."

